Saturday, Feb. 28, 2007

I asked my mom to accompany me to a hair salon for a hair cellophane. Upon arriving there, we were asked, "Ma'am, magpapaayos po kayo? Sa taas po tayo." My mom and I were like "Huh?" Then they asked again, "JS Prom po ba?" Ahhh...then I negated that notion by shaking my head and saying, "No. Hair cellophane."

So, a woman led me to wash my hair, and after that was whisked into the hands of a gentle guy/gay who reminded me of James McAvoy's character in the "Lion, The Witch and The Wardrobe" because of his curly curly hair. :) Then in an attempt to start a conversation, he asked, "Sang school ka?" I looked at him questioningly. "Mag JS ka ba?" I answered, "No.  Wala lang. Gusto ko lang magpa-cellophane." Then he said while applying the cream onto my hair, "Ang ganda naman ng buhok mo, ang itim itim. Healthy." I blushed and and could see my eyes twinkling, then quipped, "And dami ngang dandruff eh!" The faun-like guy said, "Hindi naman ah..."

Me: "Akala mo lang wala, pero meron. Meron!"

Same day, night.

My mom and dad went on a date in Tagaytay. So being the eldest, I was left in charge of my siblings--my brother, my two younger sisters, and my cousin.

Sunday.

6am--I woke up and prepared breakfast: bacon, ham, friend rice, fried eggplant, fried dried fish, two hot and spicy Pancit Canton with eggs, and pastillas for dessert.

8am--I assigned task for each person: youngest sister Niquie to tidy the garage and terrace, my cousin Carla to clean the living room and dining room, me at the kitchen, and younger sister Yamee to clean the dirty kitchen...my brother, er...was left alone to do his thesis. Yes, I was that considerate. Haha!

9am--Yamee went to her Dance Troupe practice/rehearsal. Niquie, Carla and I were left to do the cleaning upstairs...my brother, was still doing his thesis. Hehe. :P

10am--Time to cook lunch: Menudo and deep-fried potatoes with cheesy dip for dessert.

11am--Read Inquirer.

11:30--lunch time. Sending Niquie to bring Yamee's lunch to school...500 meters or so from our house.

2pm--the arrival of the "newly weds". Heehee! Mom and dad recounting their adventure over merienda they've bought for us to enjoy (or to make bawi to us) Hahaha!

What a crazy weekend!

By Asuhtah

Sometimes, people (especially those I know) might find it hard to understand me.

No worries

It's just me not wanting to be understood.
I sometimes bask myself in the idea of my being incomprehensible.

It's for my self-preservation.

But some people can't accept the idea of not knowing exactly. They really want to know no matter what, not realizing that they 're wasting their time. It's like finding the right answer for the wrong question.


So I wonder: Why can't they understand that I don't want to be understood? That's what I want them to understand--that I don't want to be understood.

For those who still want to try and exert their effort in wanting so bad to understand me WHEN I DON'T WISH TO BE UNDERSTOOD, please try to understand that I don't want you to understand me.

Now wait...

What am I doing? Trying to be understood when I am stressing the opposite?
Now, I'm negating myself.

Submerged in my own contradiction.

However insane I may be, the fact remains that I enjoy (this play of or display of) paradox.
Afterall, Emily Dickinson said:

Much madness is divinest sense.

Dare figure?

ang kulay-kalawang
kong pusa
ay sumisilip sa kawalan.
dati'y kulay kahel,
ngayo'y kalawang.
tumatanda na
si Mawie.

Ang sarap haplusin ng mga pahina...sobrang puti din nila, walang nakakasakal na pahalang na linya na tila nagdidikta lagi na, dito ka lang susulat, wag ka lalagpas.

Syempre, gumuhit agad ako ng mga imahe.

Unang saloobin na naisulat ko ay:

"kwadernong ito ay
nagdulot ng lubos
na kasiyahan;
blangkong pahina na
sisilaban ng
aking pluma;
maaari ding sabihing
duduraan, sasakalin at

Ang sarap ng pakiramdam pag nagtatae ang isipan ko...tulad din ng pagkagiliw ko sa plumang nagtatae na animo ay umiiyak o nagdurugo...makapal ang tinta at kumakalat.

Location: Semicon
Happening: Shoot of Independencia Film

Ambience: Set up first scene set and lighting.

Nag-iinstruct ako sa art department team namin regarding the look of the set. I was looking intently on what my team was doing when I suddenly felt someone touched my left arm. Instinctively, I turned my head and looked to my left, but when I did turn...

I got the biggest surprise of my day. As in, surprise SURPRISE!

When I did turn...one moment I was standing and instructing, the next Sid's lips and mine collided.

We were like...freakish! Both of us, like...woah!
Embarrassing.
Very awkward.
Strange.

I could feel my face blushing...all the blood going up to my face. I couldn't speak for like 15 seconds while Sid was repeatedly saying "sorry".

The first thing I said when I found my tongue was: "Ginulat mo ko! Next time, when you greet me good morning, magsalita ka muna bago ka humawak at bumeso." He said: "Yeah! Sorry. I will do that. Sorry talaga. From now on, I will speak first like 'Hi!' before I do that."

Hindi muna kami maka-recover bilang andaming nakakita.

Sabi ko..."let's just pretend it didn't happen." Ang awkward kasi talaga.

Pero keri lang. Nagulat lang ako ng SOBRA.

Dagdag lang sa anecdote ng buhay ko.
;)

Got this from my friend Kathlene's blog. For the benefit of those who don't know  Marcel Proust, I put some info about the questionnaire (see below). Hope this would be of help.

The Proust Questionnaire is a questionnaire about one's personality, first popularized by the responses given by the French writer Marcel Proust.

At the end of the nineteenth century, when Proust was still in his teens, he discovered a questionnaire in an English-language album belonging to his friend Antoinette, daughter of future President Felix Faure, entitled "An Album to Record Thoughts, Feelings, etc." At that time, it was a fad among wealthy English families to answer such a list of questions that revealed the tastes and aspirations of the taker.

Proust answered the questionnaire several times in his life, always with enthusiasm. The original manuscript of his answers of 1890, at the time of his volunteer internship or some little time afterwards, titled "by Marcel Proust himself," was found in 1924. 

A similar questionnaire is regularly seen in a section of the magazine Vanity Fair, answered by various celebrities.

(source--http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proust_Questionnaire)

1) How would you like to die?

While dreaming that the white rabbit is flying me to the moon.

2) If you could choose what to come back as, what would it be?

A warrior princess..not the dainty boring ones.

3) If you were to die and come back as a person or thing, what do you think it would be?

A mirror. I can have both the real world and the other world inside myself.

4) On what occasion do you lie?

If I know someone would choose to hear it than the truth...I mean, he/she knows the truth but he/she would still want to hear otherwise.

5) What are the qualities you most like in a man?

Manly? Haha!

Sensitive, honest, smart, faithful, exudes authority, and proud.

6) What are the qualities you most like in a woman?

Spunky, witty, caring, confident, and proud.

7) What are your favorite names?

Ingrid, Jura, Asta, Justa, Aria

Alexander, Wolfgang, Nicholas, Jarl, Maxwell

8) What are your most marked characteristics?

barely-there eyebrows, long legs, and big derriere

9) What do you consider the most overrated virtue?

tactless honesty and the notion of being true to oneself.

The statement "This is me." elicits the words "Aw, come on!" from me.

10)    What do you consider your greatest achievement?

Doing what I love most and fighting for it.

11)    What do you dislike most about your appearance?

that most people this time and age put importance on appearance than what's inside

12)    What do you most value in your friends?

loyalty and honesty

13)    What do you regard as the lowest depth of misery?

suicide

14)    What is it that you most dislike?

phony people...as in real phonies.

15)    What is the trait you most deplore in others?

insensitive blokes... those who love to do the talking and forget about listening

16)    What is the trait you most deplore in yourself?

My being idecisively decisive and decisively indecisive.

17)    What is your current state of mind?

deviant, rebelious, ready for battle

18)    What is your favorite journey?

Journey to the moon through plunging into the river which bears the moon's reflection.

19)    What is your favorite occupation?

Professional daydreamer.

20)    What is your greatest extravagance?

Daydreaming and escapism.

21)    What is your greatest fear?

Too much daydreaming resulting in not living in the past, the present and the future. In short, when i daydream (I do this a lot), I stop living.

22)    What is your greatest regret?

Having one.

23)    What is your idea of perfect happiness?

unconditional love amidst entropy and confusion.

24)    What is your most treasured possession?

 soul       

25)    What is your motto?

 Wake  up and live! (But then I love daydreaming and I'm a professional escapist...I'm  a complete paradox.)

 26)    What or who is the greatest love of your life?

 none at the moment

27)    When and where were you the happiest?

After painting my angst and crying (writing) my heart out through my pen's ink as my soul's tears. Oh, it's such a relief! Happiness indeed!

28)    Where would you like to live?

In the little hut (under the willow tree alongside the cold clear stream) built on the moon.

29)    Which historical figure do you most identify with?

The Unknown Warrior

30)    Which living person do you most admire?

No person in particular, but I have to take my hat off to the Christian missionaries around the globe who still continue to move despite or amidst the persecution.

31)    Which living person do you most despise?

A person who talks too much but knows too little if not nothing.

32)    Which talent would you most like to have?

play musical instruments        

33)    Which words or phrases do you overuse?

Putik (mud), my ass, okiedoks

34)    Who are your favorite writers?

I have to agree with my friend Abby. This is hard when you are really into reading books. But I crave the works of Latin American writers--Isabel Allende, Paulo Coehlo, Laura Esquivel etc.         

35)    Who are your favorite heroes of fiction?

 Peter Pan, Sherlock Holmes, Patrasche (dog of Flanders)       

36)    Who are your heroes in real life?

God; the Gray Rabbit in the moon; people who make honest living.

After the ocular for Manila film, I hurriedly went to SM Megamall to meet Melai at Power Books. We were supposed to go to AFP Theater and watch my brother perform.

BUT NO! I was late. (Yeah, I am to blame.)

Pero makakahabol pa sana kami had it not been for that woman who barged in sa pag hail ng taxi "namin". Bastos talaga.

Melai and I were hailing a taxi sa tabi ng St. Francis Square. Marami kami actually so kung nagmamadali ka, matetempt ka talaga ng mangbakaw ng cab. Pero dahil pinalaki kami ng maayos ng magulang namin at sadyang may delicadeza lang kami...hindi namin ginawang mang-agaw ng taxi ng may taxi.

May humintong taxi sa tapat namin, but I saw that it was the girl before us na nagpara sa taxi...so sabi ko kay Melai, "Wait Mel, sa babae yang taxi." So we waited. Suddenly, biglang binuksan ulit ng girl yung door sa backseat. Namimili ang driver ng lugar.

BIGLA na lng sumulpot sa kung saan itong babae na ito na nakita na na kami na ang susunod na sasakay. Kinausap niya ang driver to our disbelief (dahil sa kabstusan niya na wala na yatang tatalo pa) Nag-"yehey" pa siya at excited na tinawag ang lalaking kasama niya. And yes, nakatulala pa rin kami ni Melai. Hindi ko maibaba ang pagtaas ng kilay ko at bago pa maisara ng guy ang pinto, I couldn't help myself so I said while looking at them, "Bravo!"

They heard it. I knew it because I saw them both stared at me, taxi's door still left open. After looking at them, tumingin na ko ng diretso, and for a moment there, akala ko bababa sila dahil nakita ko ang reaction ng guy na gumalaw ang muscles sa kanyang jaw. So I thought: "Baka bababa at sasabihin sa akin na--'Ayan miss, isaksak mo sa baga mo yang taxi.'" But no! Mas gugustuhin ko pang ginawa niya yon kesa maging duwag na tanggapin na mali yung ginawa nila lalo na ng kasama niyang babae.

So naisip ko ulit na baka nasabi nung guy sa sarili niya: " Ang hirap kaya makakuha ng taxi dito. Duy, lulunukin ko na lang ang pride ko at magpapaka-walang kuwentang  lalaki at tao ako."

So umalis ang taxi at sabi ni Melai: "Grabe! May mga tao talagang ganun noh?" Sabi ko, habang nanginginig pa rin sa pangigigil: "Sorry Melai ha. HIndi ko napigilan ang sarili ko." And bilang kilala ako ni Melai, tumawa lang siya.

In short, pagdating namin sa AFP Theater, nakita ko ang father ko na nasa entrance na. Tapos na raw. Argh! Nahiya tuloy ako kay Melai.

Naku!

Hohummm...Inaantok ako pero pilit na nakikipagbuno sa aking mga talukap na habaan ang pasesnsya at manatiling dilat. Kasalukuyang nagsasalita si Digo at nagpapaliwanag ng mga bagay-bagay para sa nalalapit naming proyekto.
          Nagkasakit yata ang dila ni Gege, sa totoo lang mabibilang ang mga salitang namutawi sa kanyang bibig. Hindi ko tuloy alam kung nabigla siya sa resposibilidad ng magiging trabaho niya o sadyang nilalanghap niya ang mga espiritu namin nila Reza at Digo. Hmp! Kaya niya yan. Sus!
          Alas-siyete na. Gagabihin ako sa pagluwas sa Laguna kaya naglakas-loob akong tanungin si Digo kung matagal pa ba ang meeting. Tapos na naman daw. Ayos.
          Ayos nga. E hindi malamang dahilan ay ayaw pang umangat ng puwet ko para umalis. Nagpakasasa pa ako sa pag-upo sa komportableng sopa ng Gloria Jeans.
          Naiihi ako kaya pumunta ako sa palikuran at inilabas ang madilaw na likido. Sarap! Hooh! Paglabas ko ng banyo doon ko lang natanto na kating-kati na pala ang mga paa ko sa pag-alis.Dahil napagbigyan ko na ang luho ng puwet ko sa isang malambot na sopa, pinagbigyan ko naman ang hiling mg aking mga paa.
          Sabay-sabay kaming umalis nina Reza at Gege. Naiwan si Digo at ang kanyang kasama sa UP Dragonboat Team na si Ina. Sa Bulacan uuwi si Gege kaya doon siya sa kabilang panig ng kalsada.
          Sa loob ng MRT, nagkukuwentuhan kami ni Reza. Hindi ko pa rin mabitiwan ang isang bagay na parang ipis na ayaw mamatay-matay. Ililinga ko na lang ang aking leeg ng six degrees para tumingin sa mga tao sa loob ng MRT.
          Pagbaba ni Reza, nakita kong humawi ang mga tao at may isang babae na tila santa. Sa kanyang paglalakad ay parng may sumusunod na liwanag mula sa itaas at nakakita pa ako ng mga tatlong kalapating lumipad sa likuran niya. Tumigil siya sa harapan ko. Nagsimula ng umandar ang MRT.
          Kumusta na Asta? Tanong sa akin ng aking kaibigang si Vivika. Matagal din kaming hindi nagkita ni Vivika. Nilahad niya ang dalawang kamay niya sa akin. Tara na! Pero saan? Sigaw ng utak ko.
          Nagsimula siyang maglakad patungo sa pinakamalapit na pinto. Bumukas iyon habang umaandar ang MRT. Kinabahan ako at luminga sa paligid, sa mga taong kasakay namin. Tila balewala sa kanila ang nagaganap. Nararamdaman ko ang sampal ng hangin sa aking mga pisngi. Saan?! Nasa tulay na kami ng Guadalupe ng bigla na lamang akong hilahin ni Vivika at sa isang kurap lang ay sabay kaming bumabagsak patungo sa ilog. Pinikit ko ang aking mga mata sa pagbulusok namin sa tubig.
          Dilat na. Narinig kong sabi ni Vivika. Pero ang tubig...bakit hindi ako basa? Dumilat ako at naaninag agad ang isang imahe na nakatayo sa aking harapan. Bigla akong napakapit sa kamay ni Vivika.
          Huwag kang matakot. Di ba sabi mo nung mga bata pa tayo gusto mo siyang makilala at mamasyal sa kanyang nasasakupan? Nakita ko ang imahe ng isang napakalaking oso na nakatayo sa aking harapan. Inilahad niya ang kanyang kamay na nababalot ng mala-tubig na himaymay ng kanyang saya.
          Kumusta ka Asta? Ako si Callisto at nagagalak akong makilala ka. Para sa isang napakalaking nilalang, ang boses ng osong nagngangalang Callisto ay parang himig ng inang naghehele ng anak.
(Itutuloy)
"Si Vivika at ang Mayuming Oso"

I am so tired.
I can't move on. I can't go on.

Stupidity's blocking my way.

I want to breathe.
I can't breathe...or I choose not to breathe.
I can't stand the air around me.
It's rotten and evil...it's choking me.

I want solitude. I need to be still.

My head will burst.
My brain's full of ticking bombs.
10, 9, 8, 7 6, 5, 4, 3, 2...
Malfunctioning! It won't explode.
For a second there, I wished my head were exploding.

Then I will grow another head.
Back to square one. As pure as coconut meat.

My eyes! Oh no, tears are coming.
Then again, it's liberating to cry.
I cry
with tears
I cry
without tears
Crying without tears is the hardest ordeal.
Only then would I know
that it's my soul that's crying.

I need my room.
I want the refuge of my room.
It's my moon, my jungle, my paradise,
my palace, my world and everything I chose it to be.
Later, it will transform itself.
My room will be my coffin.

I want to die for now.
I love little deaths.
I will put my soul here in my room
and my old self will forever be
confined in this coffin.

Only then will I be renewed.
Be born again. Learn again. Live again.
I will be free.

Nag-dinner ulit kami ng bro ko.

Last thursday, I had dinner with my bro, Gian.

I saw the mad hatter came inside. He sat just beside our table.

I was eating longganisa and rice with salted and tomatoes on the side.

The mad hatter ordered rose salad with rainforest cola.

My brother was eating sardines and adobong kangkong.

He was scratching his long big nose while eating, and glancing at the clock every 15 sec. Then he noticed me.

My bro and I were having a conversation about acads and friends.

I was a little bit scared of him but foe some reason, I couldn't take my eyes off of him. Boy, I was nervous! Then slowly, his lips curved into a smile...thin wide rubber-like lips.

Feeling satisfied and full, we finally paid for our dinner. We said our goodbyes. A quiet and relaxing dinner it was!

Then he raised his cup of brewed fern bidding me goodnight.

So I wasn't able to go "Home Sweet Home" this weekend, thus I went to church (CCF at St. Francis Square) with Digo and his family. After that, they decided to go bowling. I was so thrilled!!! It has been 4 years since I last played bowling with my dad. Busy days and all make Asta's bowling gritty (or so I thought. Haha!)

The first set was awful...my muscles still adjusting and warming up, then came the second set. Im proud to say that I'm not gritty at all!!! With only few points behind Digo (who's into bowling recently...pagbigyan mo na ako Digo, bowling is really one of my fave sports. )

After bowling, we dined at Cafe Breton. Sumptuous!!!
